& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Transposition of the great arteries (TGA) is a congenital conotruncal abnormality characterized by discordant connections between the ventricles and great arteries, with the aorta originating from the right ventricle (RV), and the pulmonary artery (PA) originating from the left ventricle (LV). The two main types of TGA are complete transposition or dextro-transposition of the great arteries (D-TGA), commonly referred to as <span data-style="small-caps">d</span>-loop, and congenitally corrected transposition (CCTGA), commonly referred to as <span data-style="small-caps">l</span>-loop or L-TGA. In D-TGA, the connections between the ventricles and atria are concordant, whereas in CCTGA they are discordant, with the left atrium connected to the RV, and the right atrium connected to the LV. D-TGA manifests during the neonatal period and can be surgically managed by atrial switch operation (AtrSO), arterial switch operation (ASO), Rastelli procedure, or Nikaidoh procedure. Arrhythmia, systemic ventricular dysfunction, baffle stenosis, and baffle leak are the common complications of AtrSO, whereas supravalvular pulmonary or branch PA stenosis, neoaortic dilatation, and coronary artery narrowing are the common complications of ASO. CCTGA may manifest late in life, even in adulthood. Surgeries for associated lesions such as tricuspid regurgitation, subpulmonic stenosis, and ventricular septal defect may be performed. A double-switch operation that includes both the atrial and arterial switch operations constitutes anatomic correction for CCTGA. Imaging plays an important role in the evaluation of TGA, both before and after surgery, for helping define the anatomy, quantify hemodynamics, and evaluate complications. Transthoracic echocardiography is the first-line imaging modality for presurgical planning in children with TGA. MRI provides comprehensive morphologic and functional information, particularly in adults after surgery. CT is performed when MRI is contraindicated or expected to generate artifacts. The authors review the imaging appearances of TGA, with a focus on pre- and postsurgical imaging.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200069">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200069">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA. LA = left atrium. (a) Illustration shows the anatomy of the heart and great arteries in D-TGA. The morphologic RV is connected to the aorta, and the morphologic LV is connected to the PA. There is concordance between the atria and ventricles. IVC = inferior vena cava, SVC = superior vena cava. (b) Schematic diagram shows the hemodynamics in a patient with D-TGA. There are essentially two parallel circulations."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig1a.jpeg" height="1701" width="1332" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. D-TGA. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the anatomy of the heart and great arteries in D-TGA. The morphologic RV is connected to the aorta, and the morphologic LV is connected to the PA. There is concordance between the atria and ventricles. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(b)</b> Schematic diagram shows the hemodynamics in a patient with D-TGA. There are essentially two parallel circulations.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA. LA = left atrium. (a) Illustration shows the anatomy of the heart and great arteries in D-TGA. The morphologic RV is connected to the aorta, and the morphologic LV is connected to the PA. There is concordance between the atria and ventricles. IVC = inferior vena cava, SVC = superior vena cava. (b) Schematic diagram shows the hemodynamics in a patient with D-TGA. There are essentially two parallel circulations."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig1b.jpeg" height="1701" width="1470" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. D-TGA. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the anatomy of the heart and great arteries in D-TGA. The morphologic RV is connected to the aorta, and the morphologic LV is connected to the PA. There is concordance between the atria and ventricles. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(b)</b> Schematic diagram shows the hemodynamics in a patient with D-TGA. There are essentially two parallel circulations.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic" aria-label="Echocardiography in D-TGA. (a) Five-chamber echocardiographic image shows the PA originating from the LV. LPA = left PA, RPA = right PA. (b) Right ventricular outflow tract echocardiographic image shows the aorta originating from the RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig2a.jpeg" height="930" width="1299" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Echocardiography in D-TGA. <b>(a)</b> Five-chamber echocardiographic image shows the PA originating from the LV. <i>LPA</i> = left PA, <i>RPA</i> = right PA. <b>(b)</b> Right ventricular outflow tract echocardiographic image shows the aorta originating from the RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="Echocardiography in D-TGA. (a) Five-chamber echocardiographic image shows the PA originating from the LV. LPA = left PA, RPA = right PA. (b) Right ventricular outflow tract echocardiographic image shows the aorta originating from the RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig2b.jpeg" height="930" width="1145" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Echocardiography in D-TGA. <b>(a)</b> Five-chamber echocardiographic image shows the PA originating from the LV. <i>LPA</i> = left PA, <i>RPA</i> = right PA. <b>(b)</b> Right ventricular outflow tract echocardiographic image shows the aorta originating from the RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Radiographic appearance of D-TGA. PA chest radiograph with illustrated overlay shows cardiomegaly, with narrowing of the superior mediastinum owing to the parallel position of the great arteries. There is increased pulmonary flow. The chest radiographic appearances resembles an egg on a string (line, oval), owing to the narrow superior mediastinum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig3.jpeg" height="1094" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Radiographic appearance of D-TGA. PA chest radiograph with illustrated overlay shows cardiomegaly, with narrowing of the superior mediastinum owing to the parallel position of the great arteries. There is increased pulmonary flow. The chest radiographic appearances resembles an egg on a string (line, oval), owing to the narrow superior mediastinum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA appearance at MRI. Ao = aorta. (a) Axial cine SSFP MR image shows the aorta located anterior to and to the right of the main PA. (b) Sagittal cine SSFP MR image in the same patient shows parallel orientation of the aorta and main PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig4a.jpeg" height="1547" width="1523" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. D-TGA appearance at MRI. <i>Ao =</i> aorta. <b>(a)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image shows the aorta located anterior to and to the right of the main PA. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal cine SSFP MR image in the same patient shows parallel orientation of the aorta and main PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA appearance at MRI. Ao = aorta. (a) Axial cine SSFP MR image shows the aorta located anterior to and to the right of the main PA. (b) Sagittal cine SSFP MR image in the same patient shows parallel orientation of the aorta and main PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig4b.jpeg" height="1547" width="1223" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. D-TGA appearance at MRI. <i>Ao =</i> aorta. <b>(a)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image shows the aorta located anterior to and to the right of the main PA. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal cine SSFP MR image in the same patient shows parallel orientation of the aorta and main PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="Associated anomalies in D-TGA. (a) Short-axis reformatted cardiac CT image in a patient with D-TGA shows a small VSD (arrow) in the perimembranous septum. (b) Sagittal oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered image from cardiac CT angiography in a patient with D-TGA shows associated aortic coarctation (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig5a.jpeg" height="1682" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Associated anomalies in D-TGA. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis reformatted cardiac CT image in a patient with D-TGA shows a small VSD (arrow) in the perimembranous septum. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered image from cardiac CT angiography in a patient with D-TGA shows associated aortic coarctation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="Associated anomalies in D-TGA. (a) Short-axis reformatted cardiac CT image in a patient with D-TGA shows a small VSD (arrow) in the perimembranous septum. (b) Sagittal oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered image from cardiac CT angiography in a patient with D-TGA shows associated aortic coarctation (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig5b.jpeg" height="1682" width="1425" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Associated anomalies in D-TGA. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis reformatted cardiac CT image in a patient with D-TGA shows a small VSD (arrow) in the perimembranous septum. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered image from cardiac CT angiography in a patient with D-TGA shows associated aortic coarctation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA appearance at CT. Axial oblique reformatted maximum intensity projection image from cardiac CT angiography in a patient with D-TGA shows the LV connected to the main PA and the RV connected to the aorta (Ao)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig6.jpeg" height="1156" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. D-TGA appearance at CT. Axial oblique reformatted maximum intensity projection image from cardiac CT angiography in a patient with D-TGA shows the LV connected to the main PA and the RV connected to the aorta <i>(Ao)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="AtrSO. IVC = inferior vena cava, SVC = superior vena cava. (a) Illustration shows the Mustard procedure, in which a baffle is created by using pericardium or synthetic material. Dashed arrows = flow direction. (b) Diagram shows the hemodynamics following AtrSO. The systemic venous return is redirected to the left heart, which is connected to the PA. The pulmonary venous return (PVs) is redirected to the right heart, which is connected to the aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig7a.jpeg" height="1496" width="1340" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. AtrSO. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the Mustard procedure, in which a baffle is created by using pericardium or synthetic material. Dashed arrows = flow direction. <b>(b)</b> Diagram shows the hemodynamics following AtrSO. The systemic venous return is redirected to the left heart, which is connected to the PA. The pulmonary venous return <i>(PVs)</i> is redirected to the right heart, which is connected to the aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="AtrSO. IVC = inferior vena cava, SVC = superior vena cava. (a) Illustration shows the Mustard procedure, in which a baffle is created by using pericardium or synthetic material. Dashed arrows = flow direction. (b) Diagram shows the hemodynamics following AtrSO. The systemic venous return is redirected to the left heart, which is connected to the PA. The pulmonary venous return (PVs) is redirected to the right heart, which is connected to the aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig7b.jpeg" height="1496" width="1484" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. AtrSO. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the Mustard procedure, in which a baffle is created by using pericardium or synthetic material. Dashed arrows = flow direction. <b>(b)</b> Diagram shows the hemodynamics following AtrSO. The systemic venous return is redirected to the left heart, which is connected to the PA. The pulmonary venous return <i>(PVs)</i> is redirected to the right heart, which is connected to the aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="ASO. Illustration shows ASO for treatment of D-TGA, in which the aorta and PA are resected at the roots. The PA is brought anteriorly and anastomosed to the RV, whereas the aorta is brought posteriorly and anastomosed to the LV. The coronary arteries (pink lines) are also reimplanted. IVC = inferior vena cava, LA = left atrium, PV = pulmonary veins, SVC = superior vena cava."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig8.jpeg" height="1965" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. ASO. Illustration shows ASO for treatment of D-TGA, in which the aorta and PA are resected at the roots. The PA is brought anteriorly and anastomosed to the RV, whereas the aorta is brought posteriorly and anastomosed to the LV. The coronary arteries (pink lines) are also reimplanted. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>PV</i> = pulmonary veins, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Rastelli procedure. Illustration shows the Rastelli procedure for treatment of D-TGA, in which an intracardiac baffle connects the LV to the aorta, and an extracardiac conduit connects the RV to the PA. IVC = inferior vena cava, SVC = superior vena cava."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig9.jpeg" height="1839" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Rastelli procedure. Illustration shows the Rastelli procedure for treatment of D-TGA, in which an intracardiac baffle connects the LV to the aorta, and an extracardiac conduit connects the RV to the PA. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal imaging appearance following AtrSO. (a) Axial cine SSFP MR image shows the pulmonary baffle, with the pulmonary venous flow (arrows) diverted to the tricuspid valve and then to the RV. (b) Coronal cine SSFP MR image shows the systemic venous baffle, with the superior vena cava and inferior vena cava flow (arrows) diverted to the mitral valve and then to the LV. LA = left atrium."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig10a.jpeg" height="1339" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Normal imaging appearance following AtrSO. <b>(a)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image shows the pulmonary baffle, with the pulmonary venous flow (arrows) diverted to the tricuspid valve and then to the RV. <b>(b)</b> Coronal cine SSFP MR image shows the systemic venous baffle, with the superior vena cava and inferior vena cava flow (arrows) diverted to the mitral valve and then to the LV. <i>LA</i> = left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal imaging appearance following AtrSO. (a) Axial cine SSFP MR image shows the pulmonary baffle, with the pulmonary venous flow (arrows) diverted to the tricuspid valve and then to the RV. (b) Coronal cine SSFP MR image shows the systemic venous baffle, with the superior vena cava and inferior vena cava flow (arrows) diverted to the mitral valve and then to the LV. LA = left atrium."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig10b.jpeg" height="1339" width="1413" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Normal imaging appearance following AtrSO. <b>(a)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image shows the pulmonary baffle, with the pulmonary venous flow (arrows) diverted to the tricuspid valve and then to the RV. <b>(b)</b> Coronal cine SSFP MR image shows the systemic venous baffle, with the superior vena cava and inferior vena cava flow (arrows) diverted to the mitral valve and then to the LV. <i>LA</i> = left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Baffle stenosis after AtrSO. Coronal reconstruction from three-dimensional SSFP MR angiography in a patient who underwent AtrSO for D-TGA shows focal narrowing of the distal portion of the superior vena cava baffle (arrow), which directs flow to the mitral valve."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig11.jpeg" height="1546" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Baffle stenosis after AtrSO. Coronal reconstruction from three-dimensional SSFP MR angiography in a patient who underwent AtrSO for D-TGA shows focal narrowing of the distal portion of the superior vena cava baffle (arrow), which directs flow to the mitral valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Baffle leak after AtrSO. Four-chamber SSFP MR image in a patient who underwent AtrSO for D-TGA shows communication (arrow) between the left atrium and pulmonary venous pathway, indicating a baffle leak."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig12.jpeg" height="1465" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Baffle leak after AtrSO. Four-chamber SSFP MR image in a patient who underwent AtrSO for D-TGA shows communication (arrow) between the left atrium and pulmonary venous pathway, indicating a baffle leak.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="Systemic ventricle failure after AtrSO. (a) Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows a dilated and hypertrabeculated right RV after AtrSO. RV dysfunction (not shown) was also present, indicative of systemic ventricle failure. (b) Short-axis cardiac CT angiographic image in another patient who underwent AtrSO shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV with dysfunction. Note the bowing of the interventricular septum toward the subpulmonary LV. Green outline = epicardial contour of the LV, red outline = endocardial contour of the LV, yellow outline = endocardial contour of the RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig13a.jpeg" height="1169" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Systemic ventricle failure after AtrSO. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows a dilated and hypertrabeculated right RV after AtrSO. RV dysfunction (not shown) was also present, indicative of systemic ventricle failure. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis cardiac CT angiographic image in another patient who underwent AtrSO shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV with dysfunction. Note the bowing of the interventricular septum toward the subpulmonary LV. Green outline = epicardial contour of the LV, red outline = endocardial contour of the LV, yellow outline = endocardial contour of the RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Systemic ventricle failure after AtrSO. (a) Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows a dilated and hypertrabeculated right RV after AtrSO. RV dysfunction (not shown) was also present, indicative of systemic ventricle failure. (b) Short-axis cardiac CT angiographic image in another patient who underwent AtrSO shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV with dysfunction. Note the bowing of the interventricular septum toward the subpulmonary LV. Green outline = epicardial contour of the LV, red outline = endocardial contour of the LV, yellow outline = endocardial contour of the RV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig13b.jpeg" height="1169" width="1413" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Systemic ventricle failure after AtrSO. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows a dilated and hypertrabeculated right RV after AtrSO. RV dysfunction (not shown) was also present, indicative of systemic ventricle failure. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis cardiac CT angiographic image in another patient who underwent AtrSO shows a dilated and hypertrophied RV with dysfunction. Note the bowing of the interventricular septum toward the subpulmonary LV. Green outline = epicardial contour of the LV, red outline = endocardial contour of the LV, yellow outline = endocardial contour of the RV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal imaging appearances after ASO (Jatene procedure). Axial maximum intensity projection cardiac CT (a) and three-dimensional anatomic modeling (b) images show the anteriorly located main PA draping the aorta (Ao), which is a classic appearance after ASO following the LeCompte maneuver of the ASO. LPA = left PA, RPA = right PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig14a.jpeg" height="1421" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Normal imaging appearances after ASO (Jatene procedure). Axial maximum intensity projection cardiac CT <b>(a)</b> and three-dimensional anatomic modeling <b>(b)</b> images show the anteriorly located main PA draping the aorta <i>(Ao)</i>, which is a classic appearance after ASO following the LeCompte maneuver of the ASO. <i>LPA</i> = left PA, <i>RPA</i> = right PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal imaging appearances after ASO (Jatene procedure). Axial maximum intensity projection cardiac CT (a) and three-dimensional anatomic modeling (b) images show the anteriorly located main PA draping the aorta (Ao), which is a classic appearance after ASO following the LeCompte maneuver of the ASO. LPA = left PA, RPA = right PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig14b.jpeg" height="1419" width="1445" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Normal imaging appearances after ASO (Jatene procedure). Axial maximum intensity projection cardiac CT <b>(a)</b> and three-dimensional anatomic modeling <b>(b)</b> images show the anteriorly located main PA draping the aorta <i>(Ao)</i>, which is a classic appearance after ASO following the LeCompte maneuver of the ASO. <i>LPA</i> = left PA, <i>RPA</i> = right PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary complications of ASO. (a) Axial oblique cardiac CT reformation in a patient who underwent ASO for D-TGA shows a single coronary artery originating from the right sinus, with narrowing of the left coronary artery (arrow). (b) Short-axis phase-sensitive inversion-recovery MR image in an infant who underwent ASO for D-TGA shows subendocardial late gadolinium enhancement (arrow) in the mid anterior and anterolateral walls, indicating myocardial infarction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig15a.jpeg" height="1235" width="1194" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Coronary complications of ASO. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique cardiac CT reformation in a patient who underwent ASO for D-TGA shows a single coronary artery originating from the right sinus, with narrowing of the left coronary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis phase-sensitive inversion-recovery MR image in an infant who underwent ASO for D-TGA shows subendocardial late gadolinium enhancement (arrow) in the mid anterior and anterolateral walls, indicating myocardial infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary complications of ASO. (a) Axial oblique cardiac CT reformation in a patient who underwent ASO for D-TGA shows a single coronary artery originating from the right sinus, with narrowing of the left coronary artery (arrow). (b) Short-axis phase-sensitive inversion-recovery MR image in an infant who underwent ASO for D-TGA shows subendocardial late gadolinium enhancement (arrow) in the mid anterior and anterolateral walls, indicating myocardial infarction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig15b.jpeg" height="1235" width="1755" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Coronary complications of ASO. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique cardiac CT reformation in a patient who underwent ASO for D-TGA shows a single coronary artery originating from the right sinus, with narrowing of the left coronary artery (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis phase-sensitive inversion-recovery MR image in an infant who underwent ASO for D-TGA shows subendocardial late gadolinium enhancement (arrow) in the mid anterior and anterolateral walls, indicating myocardial infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Aortic complications after ASO. Coronal gadolinium-enhanced MR angiographic image in a patient who underwent ASO shows dilatation (double-headed arrow) of the neoaortic root (Ao)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig16.jpeg" height="1628" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Aortic complications after ASO. Coronal gadolinium-enhanced MR angiographic image in a patient who underwent ASO shows dilatation (double-headed arrow) of the neoaortic root <i>(Ao)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic" aria-label="Pulmonary complications after ASO. (a) Axial MR angiographic image in a 9-year-old girl who underwent ASO shows severe narrowing of the left PA (arrow). (b) Axial maximum intensity projection MR image in another patient shows narrowing of the right PA (arrow). Ao = aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig17a.jpeg" height="1008" width="1304" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Pulmonary complications after ASO. <b>(a)</b> Axial MR angiographic image in a 9-year-old girl who underwent ASO shows severe narrowing of the left PA (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection MR image in another patient shows narrowing of the right PA (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic" aria-label="Pulmonary complications after ASO. (a) Axial MR angiographic image in a 9-year-old girl who underwent ASO shows severe narrowing of the left PA (arrow). (b) Axial maximum intensity projection MR image in another patient shows narrowing of the right PA (arrow). Ao = aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig17b.jpeg" height="1008" width="1656" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Pulmonary complications after ASO. <b>(a)</b> Axial MR angiographic image in a 9-year-old girl who underwent ASO shows severe narrowing of the left PA (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection MR image in another patient shows narrowing of the right PA (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic" aria-label="Rastelli procedure complications. (a) Sagittal oblique gadolinium-enhanced cardiac MR angiographic image shows mild narrowing (arrow) of the extracardiac conduit between the RV and PA. (b) Three-dimensional volume-rendered MR angiographic image in another patient who underwent the Rastelli procedure for D-TGA shows an aneurysm of the aortic root and ascending aorta (AO), with a patent extracardiac conduit (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig18a.jpeg" height="1792" width="1299" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Rastelli procedure complications. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique gadolinium-enhanced cardiac MR angiographic image shows mild narrowing (arrow) of the extracardiac conduit between the RV and PA. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered MR angiographic image in another patient who underwent the Rastelli procedure for D-TGA shows an aneurysm of the aortic root and ascending aorta <i>(AO),</i> with a patent extracardiac conduit (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic" aria-label="Rastelli procedure complications. (a) Sagittal oblique gadolinium-enhanced cardiac MR angiographic image shows mild narrowing (arrow) of the extracardiac conduit between the RV and PA. (b) Three-dimensional volume-rendered MR angiographic image in another patient who underwent the Rastelli procedure for D-TGA shows an aneurysm of the aortic root and ascending aorta (AO), with a patent extracardiac conduit (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig18b.jpeg" height="1425" width="1350" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Rastelli procedure complications. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique gadolinium-enhanced cardiac MR angiographic image shows mild narrowing (arrow) of the extracardiac conduit between the RV and PA. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered MR angiographic image in another patient who underwent the Rastelli procedure for D-TGA shows an aneurysm of the aortic root and ascending aorta <i>(AO),</i> with a patent extracardiac conduit (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA. LA = left atrium. (a) Illustration shows the anatomy of the heart and great arteries in CCTGA. The aorta (Ao) originates from the RV, and the PA originates from the LV. In addition, the RA connects to the LV, and the left atrium to the RV. IVC = inferior vena cava, SVC = superior vena cava. (b) Schematic diagram shows the hemodynamics in CCTGA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig19a.jpeg" height="1529" width="1215" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. CCTGA. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the anatomy of the heart and great arteries in CCTGA. The aorta <i>(Ao)</i> originates from the RV, and the PA originates from the LV. In addition, the RA connects to the LV, and the left atrium to the RV. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(b)</b> Schematic diagram shows the hemodynamics in CCTGA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA. LA = left atrium. (a) Illustration shows the anatomy of the heart and great arteries in CCTGA. The aorta (Ao) originates from the RV, and the PA originates from the LV. In addition, the RA connects to the LV, and the left atrium to the RV. IVC = inferior vena cava, SVC = superior vena cava. (b) Schematic diagram shows the hemodynamics in CCTGA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig19b.jpeg" height="1529" width="1534" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. CCTGA. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the anatomy of the heart and great arteries in CCTGA. The aorta <i>(Ao)</i> originates from the RV, and the PA originates from the LV. In addition, the RA connects to the LV, and the left atrium to the RV. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(b)</b> Schematic diagram shows the hemodynamics in CCTGA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA at echocardiography. Axial echocardiogram shows the aorta (Ao) positioned anterior to and to the left of the main PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig20.jpeg" height="1279" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. CCTGA at echocardiography. Axial echocardiogram shows the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> positioned anterior to and to the left of the main PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA at chest radiography. Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows straightening of the left heart border. Sternotomy wires and epicardial pacemaker leads are also depicted."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig21.jpeg" height="1652" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. CCTGA at chest radiography. Posteroanterior chest radiograph shows straightening of the left heart border. Sternotomy wires and epicardial pacemaker leads are also depicted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA at MRI. (a) Axial SSFP MR image in a patient with CCTGA shows the aorta (Ao) located anterior to and left of the main PA. (b) Axial SSFP MR image caudally shows the left atrium (LA) connected to the morphologic RV on the left side. (c) Sagittal SSFP MR image shows a muscular band (straight arrow) between the atrioventricular and semilunar valve for the left-sided ventricle. This indicates a morphologic RV. Hence, the atrioventricular valve (curved arrow) is labeled tricuspid and the atrium is the left atrium (LA), with drainage of the pulmonary veins. (d) Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows the LV connected to the RA and PA, whereas the RV is connected to the aorta (AO)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig22a.jpeg" height="1169" width="1237" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. CCTGA at MRI. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP MR image in a patient with CCTGA shows the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> located anterior to and left of the main PA. <b>(b)</b> Axial SSFP MR image caudally shows the left atrium <i>(LA)</i> connected to the morphologic RV on the left side. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal SSFP MR image shows a muscular band (straight arrow) between the atrioventricular and semilunar valve for the left-sided ventricle. This indicates a morphologic RV. Hence, the atrioventricular valve (curved arrow) is labeled tricuspid and the atrium is the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, with drainage of the pulmonary veins. <b>(d)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows the LV connected to the RA and PA, whereas the RV is connected to the aorta <i>(AO)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA at MRI. (a) Axial SSFP MR image in a patient with CCTGA shows the aorta (Ao) located anterior to and left of the main PA. (b) Axial SSFP MR image caudally shows the left atrium (LA) connected to the morphologic RV on the left side. (c) Sagittal SSFP MR image shows a muscular band (straight arrow) between the atrioventricular and semilunar valve for the left-sided ventricle. This indicates a morphologic RV. Hence, the atrioventricular valve (curved arrow) is labeled tricuspid and the atrium is the left atrium (LA), with drainage of the pulmonary veins. (d) Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows the LV connected to the RA and PA, whereas the RV is connected to the aorta (AO)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig22b.jpeg" height="1169" width="1416" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. CCTGA at MRI. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP MR image in a patient with CCTGA shows the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> located anterior to and left of the main PA. <b>(b)</b> Axial SSFP MR image caudally shows the left atrium <i>(LA)</i> connected to the morphologic RV on the left side. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal SSFP MR image shows a muscular band (straight arrow) between the atrioventricular and semilunar valve for the left-sided ventricle. This indicates a morphologic RV. Hence, the atrioventricular valve (curved arrow) is labeled tricuspid and the atrium is the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, with drainage of the pulmonary veins. <b>(d)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows the LV connected to the RA and PA, whereas the RV is connected to the aorta <i>(AO)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA at MRI. (a) Axial SSFP MR image in a patient with CCTGA shows the aorta (Ao) located anterior to and left of the main PA. (b) Axial SSFP MR image caudally shows the left atrium (LA) connected to the morphologic RV on the left side. (c) Sagittal SSFP MR image shows a muscular band (straight arrow) between the atrioventricular and semilunar valve for the left-sided ventricle. This indicates a morphologic RV. Hence, the atrioventricular valve (curved arrow) is labeled tricuspid and the atrium is the left atrium (LA), with drainage of the pulmonary veins. (d) Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows the LV connected to the RA and PA, whereas the RV is connected to the aorta (AO)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig22c.jpeg" height="1403" width="1288" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span>. CCTGA at MRI. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP MR image in a patient with CCTGA shows the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> located anterior to and left of the main PA. <b>(b)</b> Axial SSFP MR image caudally shows the left atrium <i>(LA)</i> connected to the morphologic RV on the left side. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal SSFP MR image shows a muscular band (straight arrow) between the atrioventricular and semilunar valve for the left-sided ventricle. This indicates a morphologic RV. Hence, the atrioventricular valve (curved arrow) is labeled tricuspid and the atrium is the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, with drainage of the pulmonary veins. <b>(d)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows the LV connected to the RA and PA, whereas the RV is connected to the aorta <i>(AO)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22d" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA at MRI. (a) Axial SSFP MR image in a patient with CCTGA shows the aorta (Ao) located anterior to and left of the main PA. (b) Axial SSFP MR image caudally shows the left atrium (LA) connected to the morphologic RV on the left side. (c) Sagittal SSFP MR image shows a muscular band (straight arrow) between the atrioventricular and semilunar valve for the left-sided ventricle. This indicates a morphologic RV. Hence, the atrioventricular valve (curved arrow) is labeled tricuspid and the atrium is the left atrium (LA), with drainage of the pulmonary veins. (d) Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows the LV connected to the RA and PA, whereas the RV is connected to the aorta (AO)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig22d.jpeg" height="1403" width="1363" aria-labelledby="fig22d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22d</span>. CCTGA at MRI. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP MR image in a patient with CCTGA shows the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> located anterior to and left of the main PA. <b>(b)</b> Axial SSFP MR image caudally shows the left atrium <i>(LA)</i> connected to the morphologic RV on the left side. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal SSFP MR image shows a muscular band (straight arrow) between the atrioventricular and semilunar valve for the left-sided ventricle. This indicates a morphologic RV. Hence, the atrioventricular valve (curved arrow) is labeled tricuspid and the atrium is the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, with drainage of the pulmonary veins. <b>(d)</b> Four-chamber cine SSFP MR image shows the LV connected to the RA and PA, whereas the RV is connected to the aorta <i>(AO)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig22d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA with situs inversus {I,D,D}. (a) Axial SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the upper abdomen shows the spleen on the right and liver on the left, indicating situs inversus. (b) Axial cine SSFP MR image of the chest in the same patient shows the aorta (Ao) located anterior to and to the right of the PA. (c) Axial cine SSFP MR image (obtained caudal to b) shows that the aorta is connected to the RV on the right, which is connected to the left atrium (LA), whereas the LV on the left is connected to the RA. Note also the dextrocardia. (d) Sagittal cine SSFP MR image shows the connection of the RV to the aorta (Ao) and the LV to the PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig23a.jpeg" height="1075" width="1384" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. CCTGA with situs inversus {I,D,D}. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the upper abdomen shows the spleen on the right and liver on the left, indicating situs inversus. <b>(b)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image of the chest in the same patient shows the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> located anterior to and to the right of the PA. <b>(c)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image (obtained caudal to <b>b</b>) shows that the aorta is connected to the RV on the right, which is connected to the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, whereas the LV on the left is connected to the RA. Note also the dextrocardia. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal cine SSFP MR image shows the connection of the RV to the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and the LV to the PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA with situs inversus {I,D,D}. (a) Axial SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the upper abdomen shows the spleen on the right and liver on the left, indicating situs inversus. (b) Axial cine SSFP MR image of the chest in the same patient shows the aorta (Ao) located anterior to and to the right of the PA. (c) Axial cine SSFP MR image (obtained caudal to b) shows that the aorta is connected to the RV on the right, which is connected to the left atrium (LA), whereas the LV on the left is connected to the RA. Note also the dextrocardia. (d) Sagittal cine SSFP MR image shows the connection of the RV to the aorta (Ao) and the LV to the PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig23b.jpeg" height="1075" width="1268" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. CCTGA with situs inversus {I,D,D}. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the upper abdomen shows the spleen on the right and liver on the left, indicating situs inversus. <b>(b)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image of the chest in the same patient shows the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> located anterior to and to the right of the PA. <b>(c)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image (obtained caudal to <b>b</b>) shows that the aorta is connected to the RV on the right, which is connected to the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, whereas the LV on the left is connected to the RA. Note also the dextrocardia. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal cine SSFP MR image shows the connection of the RV to the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and the LV to the PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23c" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA with situs inversus {I,D,D}. (a) Axial SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the upper abdomen shows the spleen on the right and liver on the left, indicating situs inversus. (b) Axial cine SSFP MR image of the chest in the same patient shows the aorta (Ao) located anterior to and to the right of the PA. (c) Axial cine SSFP MR image (obtained caudal to b) shows that the aorta is connected to the RV on the right, which is connected to the left atrium (LA), whereas the LV on the left is connected to the RA. Note also the dextrocardia. (d) Sagittal cine SSFP MR image shows the connection of the RV to the aorta (Ao) and the LV to the PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig23c.jpeg" height="1114" width="1393" aria-labelledby="fig23c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23c</span>. CCTGA with situs inversus {I,D,D}. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the upper abdomen shows the spleen on the right and liver on the left, indicating situs inversus. <b>(b)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image of the chest in the same patient shows the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> located anterior to and to the right of the PA. <b>(c)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image (obtained caudal to <b>b</b>) shows that the aorta is connected to the RV on the right, which is connected to the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, whereas the LV on the left is connected to the RA. Note also the dextrocardia. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal cine SSFP MR image shows the connection of the RV to the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and the LV to the PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig23c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23d" class="graphic" aria-label="CCTGA with situs inversus {I,D,D}. (a) Axial SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the upper abdomen shows the spleen on the right and liver on the left, indicating situs inversus. (b) Axial cine SSFP MR image of the chest in the same patient shows the aorta (Ao) located anterior to and to the right of the PA. (c) Axial cine SSFP MR image (obtained caudal to b) shows that the aorta is connected to the RV on the right, which is connected to the left atrium (LA), whereas the LV on the left is connected to the RA. Note also the dextrocardia. (d) Sagittal cine SSFP MR image shows the connection of the RV to the aorta (Ao) and the LV to the PA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig23d.jpeg" height="1114" width="1253" aria-labelledby="fig23d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23d</span>. CCTGA with situs inversus {I,D,D}. <b>(a)</b> Axial SSFP MR image obtained at the level of the upper abdomen shows the spleen on the right and liver on the left, indicating situs inversus. <b>(b)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image of the chest in the same patient shows the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> located anterior to and to the right of the PA. <b>(c)</b> Axial cine SSFP MR image (obtained caudal to <b>b</b>) shows that the aorta is connected to the RV on the right, which is connected to the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, whereas the LV on the left is connected to the RA. Note also the dextrocardia. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal cine SSFP MR image shows the connection of the RV to the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and the LV to the PA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig23d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic" aria-label="Double-switch operation. (a) Illustration shows the double-switch operation for CCTGA. Arrows = direction of flow, IVC = inferior vena cava, PV = pulmonary vein, SVC = superior vena cava. (b) Schematic diagram shows the pulmonic and systemic circulations after the double-switch operation. Solid and dashed arrows = direction of flow after the procedure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig24a.jpeg" height="1558" width="1364" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. Double-switch operation. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the double-switch operation for CCTGA. Arrows = direction of flow, <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>PV</i> = pulmonary vein, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(b)</b> Schematic diagram shows the pulmonic and systemic circulations after the double-switch operation. Solid and dashed arrows = direction of flow after the procedure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic" aria-label="Double-switch operation. (a) Illustration shows the double-switch operation for CCTGA. Arrows = direction of flow, IVC = inferior vena cava, PV = pulmonary vein, SVC = superior vena cava. (b) Schematic diagram shows the pulmonic and systemic circulations after the double-switch operation. Solid and dashed arrows = direction of flow after the procedure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig24b.jpeg" height="1566" width="1579" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. Double-switch operation. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the double-switch operation for CCTGA. Arrows = direction of flow, <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>PV</i> = pulmonary vein, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(b)</b> Schematic diagram shows the pulmonic and systemic circulations after the double-switch operation. Solid and dashed arrows = direction of flow after the procedure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic" aria-label="Rastelli-Senning procedure. SVC = superior vena cava. (a) Coronal SSFP MR image in a patient who underwent the Rastelli-Senning procedure shows the appearance of a systemic venous baffle. IVC = inferior vena cava. (b) Three-dimensional volume-rendered MR angiographic image in a different patient shows the connections after the Rastelli-Senning procedure for CCTGA, with an extracardiac conduit (arrow). Ao = aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig25a.jpeg" height="1269" width="1421" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span>. Rastelli-Senning procedure. <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(a)</b> Coronal SSFP MR image in a patient who underwent the Rastelli-Senning procedure shows the appearance of a systemic venous baffle. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered MR angiographic image in a different patient shows the connections after the Rastelli-Senning procedure for CCTGA, with an extracardiac conduit (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic" aria-label="Rastelli-Senning procedure. SVC = superior vena cava. (a) Coronal SSFP MR image in a patient who underwent the Rastelli-Senning procedure shows the appearance of a systemic venous baffle. IVC = inferior vena cava. (b) Three-dimensional volume-rendered MR angiographic image in a different patient shows the connections after the Rastelli-Senning procedure for CCTGA, with an extracardiac conduit (arrow). Ao = aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig25b.jpeg" height="1269" width="1218" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span>. Rastelli-Senning procedure. <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(a)</b> Coronal SSFP MR image in a patient who underwent the Rastelli-Senning procedure shows the appearance of a systemic venous baffle. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered MR angiographic image in a different patient shows the connections after the Rastelli-Senning procedure for CCTGA, with an extracardiac conduit (arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic" aria-label="Complications of Rastelli-Senning procedure. Sagittal MR angiographic image in a patient who underwent the Rastelli-Senning procedure for CCTGA shows focal obstruction (arrow) of the extracardiac conduit."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig26.jpeg" height="1021" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Complications of Rastelli-Senning procedure. Sagittal MR angiographic image in a patient who underwent the Rastelli-Senning procedure for CCTGA shows focal obstruction (arrow) of the extracardiac conduit.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary arterial patterns in TGA. Illustrations show the configuration of the aortic sinuses (red ovals) in patients with D-TGA. When the aorta is anterior to and to the right of the PA, the facing sinuses are leftward-anterior and rightward-posterior (left). When the great arteries are directly anterior-posterior, the facing sinuses are leftward and rightward (middle). When the great arteries are directly side-by-side, the facing sinuses are anterior and posterior (right)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig27.jpeg" height="1291" width="3199" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Coronary arterial patterns in TGA. Illustrations show the configuration of the aortic sinuses (red ovals) in patients with D-TGA. When the aorta is anterior to and to the right of the PA, the facing sinuses are leftward-anterior and rightward-posterior (left). When the great arteries are directly anterior-posterior, the facing sinuses are leftward and rightward (middle). When the great arteries are directly side-by-side, the facing sinuses are anterior and posterior (right).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic" aria-label="Usual pattern of coronary arterial anatomy in D-TGA. (a) Illustration shows the usual pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA. CA = coronary artery. (b) Axial coronary CT angiographic image in a patient with D-TGA ({S,D,D}) who underwent AtrSO shows a left coronary artery originating from the left-facing sinus, bifurcating into the left anterior descending artery (LAD) (anterior interventricular groove) and left circumflex artery (LCX) (in the left atrioventricular groove). The right coronary artery (RCA) arises from the right posterior facing sinus (ie, the usual pattern)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig28a.jpeg" height="1099" width="1199" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span>. Usual pattern of coronary arterial anatomy in D-TGA. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the usual pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA. <i>CA</i> = coronary artery. <b>(b)</b> Axial coronary CT angiographic image in a patient with D-TGA ({S,D,D}) who underwent AtrSO shows a left coronary artery originating from the left-facing sinus, bifurcating into the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i> (anterior interventricular groove) and left circumflex artery <i>(LCX)</i> (in the left atrioventricular groove). The right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arises from the right posterior facing sinus (ie, the usual pattern).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic" aria-label="Usual pattern of coronary arterial anatomy in D-TGA. (a) Illustration shows the usual pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA. CA = coronary artery. (b) Axial coronary CT angiographic image in a patient with D-TGA ({S,D,D}) who underwent AtrSO shows a left coronary artery originating from the left-facing sinus, bifurcating into the left anterior descending artery (LAD) (anterior interventricular groove) and left circumflex artery (LCX) (in the left atrioventricular groove). The right coronary artery (RCA) arises from the right posterior facing sinus (ie, the usual pattern)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig28b.jpeg" height="1497" width="1467" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span>. Usual pattern of coronary arterial anatomy in D-TGA. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the usual pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA. <i>CA</i> = coronary artery. <b>(b)</b> Axial coronary CT angiographic image in a patient with D-TGA ({S,D,D}) who underwent AtrSO shows a left coronary artery originating from the left-facing sinus, bifurcating into the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i> (anterior interventricular groove) and left circumflex artery <i>(LCX)</i> (in the left atrioventricular groove). The right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arises from the right posterior facing sinus (ie, the usual pattern).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29a" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA with the left circumflex artery arising from the right coronary artery (RCA). (a) Illustration shows the second most common pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA, with the left circumflex artery (LCX) originating from the right coronary artery. (b, c) Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left anterior descending artery (LAD) arising from the left-facing sinus, whereas the right coronary artery (RCA) arises from the right-facing sinus. The left circumflex artery (CIRC) originates from the right coronary artery and has a retropulmonic course."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig29a.jpeg" height="1189" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig29a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29a</span>. D-TGA with the left circumflex artery arising from the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i>. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the second most common pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA, with the left circumflex artery <i>(LCX)</i> originating from the right coronary artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i> arising from the left-facing sinus, whereas the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arises from the right-facing sinus. The left circumflex artery <i>(CIRC)</i> originates from the right coronary artery and has a retropulmonic course.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig29a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29b" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA with the left circumflex artery arising from the right coronary artery (RCA). (a) Illustration shows the second most common pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA, with the left circumflex artery (LCX) originating from the right coronary artery. (b, c) Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left anterior descending artery (LAD) arising from the left-facing sinus, whereas the right coronary artery (RCA) arises from the right-facing sinus. The left circumflex artery (CIRC) originates from the right coronary artery and has a retropulmonic course."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig29b.jpeg" height="1098" width="1213" aria-labelledby="fig29b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29b</span>. D-TGA with the left circumflex artery arising from the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i>. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the second most common pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA, with the left circumflex artery <i>(LCX)</i> originating from the right coronary artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i> arising from the left-facing sinus, whereas the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arises from the right-facing sinus. The left circumflex artery <i>(CIRC)</i> originates from the right coronary artery and has a retropulmonic course.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig29b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29c" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA with the left circumflex artery arising from the right coronary artery (RCA). (a) Illustration shows the second most common pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA, with the left circumflex artery (LCX) originating from the right coronary artery. (b, c) Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left anterior descending artery (LAD) arising from the left-facing sinus, whereas the right coronary artery (RCA) arises from the right-facing sinus. The left circumflex artery (CIRC) originates from the right coronary artery and has a retropulmonic course."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig29c.jpeg" height="1098" width="1739" aria-labelledby="fig29c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29c</span>. D-TGA with the left circumflex artery arising from the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i>. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the second most common pattern of coronary origins in D-TGA, with the left circumflex artery <i>(LCX)</i> originating from the right coronary artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i> arising from the left-facing sinus, whereas the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arises from the right-facing sinus. The left circumflex artery <i>(CIRC)</i> originates from the right coronary artery and has a retropulmonic course.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig29c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30a" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA with an inverted pattern of the coronary arteries. (a) Illustration shows an inverted pattern of the coronary origins in D-TGA, with the right coronary artery (Right CA) originating from the left-facing sinus and the left coronary artery (Left CA) originating from the right-facing sinus. (b, c) Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left main artery (Left main) arising from the posterior-facing sinus, and the right coronary artery (RCA) arising from the anterior-facing sinus. Note the bifurcation of the left main artery into the left anterior descending artery (LAD) and left circumflex artery (LCX)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig30a.jpeg" height="1501" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig30a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30a</span>. D-TGA with an inverted pattern of the coronary arteries. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows an inverted pattern of the coronary origins in D-TGA, with the right coronary artery <i>(Right CA)</i> originating from the left-facing sinus and the left coronary artery <i>(Left CA)</i> originating from the right-facing sinus. <b>(b, c)</b> Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left main artery <i>(Left main)</i> arising from the posterior-facing sinus, and the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arising from the anterior-facing sinus. Note the bifurcation of the left main artery into the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i> and left circumflex artery <i>(LCX).</i><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig30a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30b" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA with an inverted pattern of the coronary arteries. (a) Illustration shows an inverted pattern of the coronary origins in D-TGA, with the right coronary artery (Right CA) originating from the left-facing sinus and the left coronary artery (Left CA) originating from the right-facing sinus. (b, c) Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left main artery (Left main) arising from the posterior-facing sinus, and the right coronary artery (RCA) arising from the anterior-facing sinus. Note the bifurcation of the left main artery into the left anterior descending artery (LAD) and left circumflex artery (LCX)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig30b.jpeg" height="1501" width="1332" aria-labelledby="fig30b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30b</span>. D-TGA with an inverted pattern of the coronary arteries. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows an inverted pattern of the coronary origins in D-TGA, with the right coronary artery <i>(Right CA)</i> originating from the left-facing sinus and the left coronary artery <i>(Left CA)</i> originating from the right-facing sinus. <b>(b, c)</b> Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left main artery <i>(Left main)</i> arising from the posterior-facing sinus, and the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arising from the anterior-facing sinus. Note the bifurcation of the left main artery into the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i> and left circumflex artery <i>(LCX).</i><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig30b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30c" class="graphic" aria-label="D-TGA with an inverted pattern of the coronary arteries. (a) Illustration shows an inverted pattern of the coronary origins in D-TGA, with the right coronary artery (Right CA) originating from the left-facing sinus and the left coronary artery (Left CA) originating from the right-facing sinus. (b, c) Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left main artery (Left main) arising from the posterior-facing sinus, and the right coronary artery (RCA) arising from the anterior-facing sinus. Note the bifurcation of the left main artery into the left anterior descending artery (LAD) and left circumflex artery (LCX)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig30c.jpeg" height="1501" width="1140" aria-labelledby="fig30c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30c</span>. D-TGA with an inverted pattern of the coronary arteries. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows an inverted pattern of the coronary origins in D-TGA, with the right coronary artery <i>(Right CA)</i> originating from the left-facing sinus and the left coronary artery <i>(Left CA)</i> originating from the right-facing sinus. <b>(b, c)</b> Consecutive axial maximum intensity projection coronary CT angiographic images show the left main artery <i>(Left main)</i> arising from the posterior-facing sinus, and the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arising from the anterior-facing sinus. Note the bifurcation of the left main artery into the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i> and left circumflex artery <i>(LCX).</i><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig30c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustration shows an inverted right coronary artery (RCA) and left circumflex artery (LCX)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig31.jpeg" height="1518" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig31" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31</span>. Illustration shows an inverted right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> and left circumflex artery <i>(LCX)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig31">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32a" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary anatomy in CCTGA. (a) Illustration shows the anatomy of the coronary arteries in CCTGA. CA = coronary artery. (b, c) Axial maximum intensity projection CT images show that the right coronary artery (RCA) arises from the left-facing sinus, courses in the left atrioventricular groove, and supplies the RV in a patient with CCTGA {S,L,L}. The right-facing sinus gives rise to the left anterior descending artery (LAD), which courses anteriorly in the interventricular groove, and the left circumflex artery (LCX) courses in the right atrioventricular groove, supplying the lateral LV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig32a.jpeg" height="1306" width="1260" aria-labelledby="fig32a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32a</span>. Coronary anatomy in CCTGA. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the anatomy of the coronary arteries in CCTGA. <i>CA</i> = coronary artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection CT images show that the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arises from the left-facing sinus, courses in the left atrioventricular groove, and supplies the RV in a patient with CCTGA {S,L,L}. The right-facing sinus gives rise to the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i>, which courses anteriorly in the interventricular groove, and the left circumflex artery <i>(LCX)</i> courses in the right atrioventricular groove, supplying the lateral LV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig32a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32b" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary anatomy in CCTGA. (a) Illustration shows the anatomy of the coronary arteries in CCTGA. CA = coronary artery. (b, c) Axial maximum intensity projection CT images show that the right coronary artery (RCA) arises from the left-facing sinus, courses in the left atrioventricular groove, and supplies the RV in a patient with CCTGA {S,L,L}. The right-facing sinus gives rise to the left anterior descending artery (LAD), which courses anteriorly in the interventricular groove, and the left circumflex artery (LCX) courses in the right atrioventricular groove, supplying the lateral LV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig32b.jpeg" height="1306" width="1251" aria-labelledby="fig32b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32b</span>. Coronary anatomy in CCTGA. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the anatomy of the coronary arteries in CCTGA. <i>CA</i> = coronary artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection CT images show that the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arises from the left-facing sinus, courses in the left atrioventricular groove, and supplies the RV in a patient with CCTGA {S,L,L}. The right-facing sinus gives rise to the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i>, which courses anteriorly in the interventricular groove, and the left circumflex artery <i>(LCX)</i> courses in the right atrioventricular groove, supplying the lateral LV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig32b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32c" class="graphic" aria-label="Coronary anatomy in CCTGA. (a) Illustration shows the anatomy of the coronary arteries in CCTGA. CA = coronary artery. (b, c) Axial maximum intensity projection CT images show that the right coronary artery (RCA) arises from the left-facing sinus, courses in the left atrioventricular groove, and supplies the RV in a patient with CCTGA {S,L,L}. The right-facing sinus gives rise to the left anterior descending artery (LAD), which courses anteriorly in the interventricular groove, and the left circumflex artery (LCX) courses in the right atrioventricular groove, supplying the lateral LV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200069/asset/images/large/rg.2021200069.fig32c.jpeg" height="1306" width="1196" aria-labelledby="fig32c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32c</span>. Coronary anatomy in CCTGA. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the anatomy of the coronary arteries in CCTGA. <i>CA</i> = coronary artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection CT images show that the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> arises from the left-facing sinus, courses in the left atrioventricular groove, and supplies the RV in a patient with CCTGA {S,L,L}. The right-facing sinus gives rise to the left anterior descending artery <i>(LAD)</i>, which courses anteriorly in the interventricular groove, and the left circumflex artery <i>(LCX)</i> courses in the right atrioventricular groove, supplying the lateral LV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200069&amp;id=fig32c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Cohen MS, Eidem BW, Cetta F, et al. Multimodality Imaging Guidelines of Patients with Transposition of the Great Arteries: A Report from the American Society of Echocardiography Developed in Collaboration with the Society for Cardiovascular Magnetic Resonance and the Society of Cardiovascular Computed Tomography. <em>J Am Soc Echocardiogr</em> 2016;29(7):571–621.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.echo.2016.04.002">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27372954/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Multimodality+Imaging+Guidelines+of+Patients+with+Transposition+of+the+Great+Arteries%3A+A+Report+from+the+American+Society+of+Echocardiography+Developed+in+Collaboration+with+the+Society+for+Cardiovascular+Magnetic+Resonance+and+the+Society+of+Cardiovascular+Computed+Tomography&amp;author=MS+Cohen&amp;author=BW+Eidem&amp;author=F+Cetta&amp;publication_year=2016&amp;journal=J+Am+Soc+Echocardiogr&amp;pages=571-621&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.echo.2016.04.002&amp;pmid=27372954">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-co